Notes: Got it clean! Felt solid and really dialed throughout it too. Very stoked to bag my first .12a!
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Ghetto Wall

Notes: First effort greased out of the crux pocket.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Ghetto Wall

Notes: The steep stuff up high is so sick. I realized I dodged 2 bolts of the direct line just after Kathmandu which looks like it adds some good climbing instead of escaping right to a standing rest. If you do this again you should try that.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Ghetto Wall

Notes: Very soft for the grade, I would say .10b and even then it’s like 3 moves. Pretty cool moves but then the rest of the route is forgettable.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Ghetto Wall

Notes: Pretty sure this is the line we did. Good fun!
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Planet of the Apes Wall

Notes: Took a hang up top, feeling hosed from the day. Easy down low to some fun tough stuff on high.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Planet of the Apes Wall

Notes: Sent the crux much easier this time, but still having trouble with the crack-y thing up high.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Malibu Creek State Park > Planet of the Apes Wall

Notes:
Max cupped hands for me. Quite easy for my mitts.
Recommended rack: 4-6x(3)
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Reservoir Wall

Notes: Led to the roof, aided the roof to then TR practice it. Strike mission with Justin, very fun! So effin sandy. This thing is absolutely insane, anyone who can turn the lip on this rig is a monster. The method that worked well for me is to scoot the butt by full palming the lip, then driving the legs bag up so you don’t slip out. As for getting in and out, only god knows.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Fin Wall

Notes: 1 hang at crux. This route is awesome and feels very doable. Some offset off fingers takes you below a roof. A knee bar and a hard pull on some tips brings you to some not-so-bad fingers. Look for an escape to a ledge on your left around the arete for a rest. The crux is two bodylengths of hard pulling with poor feet. The top requires some weird movement but isn’t too bad.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Reservoir Wall

Notes:
Not my proudest send but not a total dogghouse either. 1 fall on the first section and two exhausto-hangs through the main line. The first section requires a few strong pulls, then get that right foot in the big pod and start stemming swimming that left hand TD. Don’t place too close to the roof, rope drag would suck. Enjoy infinite crammed 2’s to big 1’s, you can jam this size well! Rest up, bump out a short section of crammed 1’s to a thank god jug. Then another rest into low angle 0.75/0.5’s to the chain where getting a good corner smear is critical. Crazy long, crazy good, you have to come back for this one!
Recommended rack: 3x(0.5), 4x(0.75), 6x(1), 4x(2), 2x(3).
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Reservoir Wall

Notes:
Cool facey moves with some small gear. Crank some good locks to a fine rest then bump out a layback section that goes to jams sooner than you think.
Recommended rack: 1x(0.2-4), double 0.75 and down if more gear is desired.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Notes: Way harder than Blue Sky Mining to its right. The 0.75’s is mega tough, steep and poor feet. Sandy for us too. The layback is not too bad but also harder than the layback section on the right.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Route: unnamed classic hand crack aka Gold Crown
Notes: Mega route. So long and tasty. Layback not so bad. I thought the 1’s roof down low was the hardest part. Difficult for me to jam nicely so I just punched a layback through it. Cruise forever to the 4’s roof, which I thought wasn’t too bad with my mitts. Take a nice rest in the knee jam and bump out the final section.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Notes:
Redpoint attempt after TR. One hang at crux after throwing foot but not quite getting it high enough. The key is to be patient, get the good butterfly jam with both of your palms pointed right. Be sure to get your low foot high and not too deep and throw that right foot above your head! The rest of the route is chill.
Recommended rack: 1x(0.75), 1x(3), 1x(4), 3-4x(5)
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Notes: TR attempt. 1 hang at crux.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Notes:
Super all-time. Crazy enjoyable hand cruising for 2/3rds of it. Rest up in the pod and cruise some slightly less than vertical 1->0.75->0.5 with plenty of foot pods and relief.
Triples 0.5-3
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Broken Tooth

Notes:
Led all pitches with Luke. One whip and one take at the P2 crux. Everything else clean and in good style. Absolutely incredible climbing in an absolutely incredible position with great friends!
P1 starts with a tough move into the crack proper, using the leaning right crack for locks and feet. Easy until the finish where you have to burl through some steep wide.
P2 crux is also off the deck. An easy foot ramp takes you to a tips crack where a good nut and a high 0.2 can be placed. Crank off some good locks, place a good piece high and be ready to fire. Don’t bother with the arete on the left, focus on cranking slightly off fingers and driving hard with that right foot. Getting your LHTU in the slot finishes the crux. The rest of the pitch is steep but fine.
P3 climbs the improbably roof, stay fresh for it, the exposure is insane and the moves legit! The final squeeze is totally fine if you climb it mostly left side in. Plenty of rails and holds. Keep an eye out for the skull!
The summit is awesome, took plenty of newds and enjoyed the views!
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > North Six Shooter Peak

Notes: End of day lap. A fine route, a little dirty and the hands get wide. Cool views and cool exit move.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Battle of the Bulge Buttress

Notes:
Another year, another flail on cave route. If I actually want to send this I should probably try a lap on TR and try it when I’m fresh instead of when I’m already super worked! These crammed 1’s are just so tight for me, it’s ring locks all the way or uber thin swimming. I still recommend not getting your right foot in, it just always barn doors me out. It’s so hard to trust your feet on this for some reason. There is a clear rail on the back wall that designates when you can start stemming. From there, the crack will widen and some relief is found.
Recommended rack: 2x(0.75), 8-10(1x), 2x(2).
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Battle of the Bulge Buttress

Notes: A good warmup for the area as it starts with some thin hands and the flare requires some oomph.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Battle of the Bulge Buttress

Notes:
Pretty stellar hands for me throughout. Makes you huff and puff hard through the steepness.
Recommended rack: 2x(0.5-1), 4-6x(2), 2-4x(3)
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Battle of the Bulge Buttress

Notes:
All time route for it’s cool feature and varied movement. Took some power yelps and I may have blacked out at the final moves but I sent! Some blue collar work gets you under the roof where a nice knee bar rest awaits you. Pulling the roof is much easier than it looks. To the pod is nice baggy 1’s with good foot chips so get sequential. The crux is after the pod, getting situated on some ring locks. Left hand in the top of the pod, then get a nice RH ring lock, set some higher feet in the pod and bang a RHTD to a locker constriction. Bang out a few powerful moves to some nice feet and clean it up easy.
Recommended rack: 1x(0.5), 3x(0.75), 5x(1), 1x(2), 2x(3), 1x(5), optional 4.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Battle of the Bulge Buttress

Notes:
Nasty route. Awkward tips, to sandy laybacks. Short but mean, I would not climb it again.
Recommended rack: 1x(0.2), 2x(0.3), 2x(0.4), 1x(0.5), 1x(0.75)
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > The Wall

Notes:
Absolutely stellar climb, every dang size and perfect rock.
2 hangs, one in the 0.5 section and one after placing for the tips. There is a thank god flaring handjam before the business, the sequence is much nicer if you hit it with the left and go from there. There are nice pods for feet that take the edge off. The boulder problem just requires getting both hands on the rail and hucking a high left foot. The start takes a 0.5 and the finish a 3. I would say the hardest part is placing the final 0.3 from the sandy crimps.
Double rack 0.3-3 and an extra 0.5+3 is perfect.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > The Wall

Notes: Gave it a second go and biffed the final move, big bummer!
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > The Wall

Notes:
Tronsight. Chill hands that alternates baggy 1’s to good 2’s. Good rests. Some good pods through the switch, place, then crank out a few reps of ring locks. Don’t place pro through this section, just gun it to a nice rest out left where you can chill and place pro! Then finish with a few ring locks to a thank god handjam and voila.
Recommended rack:
1x(0.5) 3x (0.75) 6x(1) 4x(2) 1x(3)
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > The Wall

Notes: Quick end of day lap. Such crazy good slammer hands.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Way Rambo

Notes:
1 hang prior to the pre-roof rest. 1 big fall and a hang through the roof. The long 1’s section went very smooth and I’m actually probably most proud of that. You are rewarded with a jug to pull into the rest and a pretty solid active rest. The section after is best turned into a quick layback so you can your foot into the divot to prep for the roof. A 1+2 with an alpine is bomber. It’s critical you don’t try to place until after you’re out of the layback past the roof. Pull fucking hard and send it. You have to reach far with the right to find anything worth grabbing when trying to turn the roof. Once you latch your left hand it’s easy to pull into the crack and the crux is over. The fall is clean so seeeeend it!!!
1x(0.5), 8x(1), 2x(2), 1x(3). Save a 1 for after the turn.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Way Rambo

Notes: Really chill tbh, unlimited no hands knee locks. Very fun for practicing hand-fist stacks.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Way Rambo

Notes: Crazy long! Damn steep at the end. A key foot dish and a big reach to a finger jam save the day. Almost all friendly hands size at big 2’s and small 3’s.
Location: Utah > Southeast Utah > Indian Creek > Way Rambo

Notes: As good as I remember. A little slick at the low crux.

Notes: Crux beta for me, right hand on left crimpy part of obvious hold. Crux left hand to right part that is better. Right foot out right, don’t heel hook, use your toe. Bang out right through an intermediate side pull to a deep hold. To finish pull hard and over the lip.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: Two laps. Once through the first Mak crux, cross right hand out left, pull hard on edges. Eventually get your right gastoning out right, a high left foot and then press and fire for the juggy hueco. Rest at the hueco, then use a left Gaston to pull your knee into the hueco and knee bar. Finagle your left hand to the obvious hueco and fire through some big moves on big holds.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

It’s been like two months since I’ve led outside and I felt it on this pitch, even though I feel very strong. Good layback practice though, would def repeat maybe from the true start.
Location: California > Tahquitz & Suicide Rocks > Tahquitz Rock > (g) West Face > West Face - Right Side

Notes: TR doggin', incomplete attempt. Made it to the big drop knee cross over move, go high!
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: Another lap, nice and smooth. I think I'm ready!

Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes:
- 4 RS with a draw right of the horn.
- 0.3 RS just left of the finger jam in the horizontal.
- 0.4 LS above first crux.
- 0.4 RS from hand jam.
- 0.3 and 0.75 with draw LS above second crux.

On the first crux def bump the left a little extra higher to make the pull over easier. Very little extra effort and you gain a lot from it.

I found some awesome beta for the second crux. Once you’ve sunk the finger jam with the right (should be deep knuckle of pointer and middle not shallow with ring and pinky), bump the left hand to a left facing crimp. It is best to go for the finger jam with your left foot on the wall and your right on a marginal rail. This sets you up to release the hand jam into the crimp nicely. High feet and fire left hand through slopers to good stuff.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: Disappointing fall after the crux at the second to last bolt! Just gassed out. Crux sequence goes smoothly with heel hooks and ample holds out left of the arete. Save some gas because not all the huecos are positive. Most huecos are obvious but there’s a small one out right at the second to last bolt that is crucial.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: A nice warmup.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: A few tries. The top out still gives me pause. 2018 me would be proud.

Notes: A few goes. Big moves and not too bad.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > * Santa Barbara Bouldering > The Brickyard > Dancing Outlaw Boulder

Notes: A handful of tries, crimpy and hard for V1 imo.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > * Santa Barbara Bouldering > The Brickyard > Ant Boulder

Notes:
With Ross. Led evens. Fell twice at the crux. Everything else went in good style.

P1: A nice warmup, best linked into pitch 2.
P2: A short tips crux, be sure to use a foot out right. Then a more powerful fingers crux. Both short and connected with easy ground.
P3: Easy ground to the crux traverse. You can go low across to the steep handcrack, or go straight up to a downward facing flake to pull right directly across to the jugs. We went low.
P4: Sustained pitch. Lots of stemming in the chimney corner thing into some steep pulls. Finished with parallel cracks where I stayed left which felt more like .10+, beta says to move into the right crack halfway or so. This one will make you breath hard.
P5: Relaxed .10a pitch, mostly hands. Cruiser.
P6: The money pitch. Starts with tricky stemming, goes easier than it looks. Use those gashes in the left wall! Roof pull has good gear and is actually pretty low key. The following section is steep and pumpy. The finger crack that follows is also steep and pumpy. This is a hard pitch even before the crux.
P6: Crux. I split this pitch. Be tough and carry it through next time. 2 black totems and a 0.5 are all you need to protect it. Pull on good locks. I would stay in the cracks until you can get the your right hand nicely into the top right pod. Then you can cleanly  get a hand on each crimp and reach far left around the arete for a good hold, lower is juicier and pull around.
P7: Steep but not too bad section to start. Tough part is the step across, just make sure you traverse midway where there are nice fins to grab and not high up at the roof where it is extra tough.
P8: Long pitch of steep glory hands. Enjoy it, you earned it.

This climb is awesome. Sustained, steep, varied, aesthetic, every pitch awesome. Definitely a lifetime climb for me and I’m so glad to have gotten on it.
Location: California > High Sierra > 02 - The Sawtooth Ridge > Incredible Hulk

Notes: Led evens, with Ross. Short cruxes but even when not cruxy this thing is sustained! Classic-ness definitely comes from its consistent steepness and variety of corner movement. Tricky move to gain the pin, and a strong move out of it. Keep your hands low if you’ve got to use smears ya schmuck!
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Bishop Area > Pine Creek Canyon > Scheelite Canyon / Pratt's Crack Gully > Armando's Stilletto / Rites of Spring

Notes: Three solid attempts. Figured out how to pass through the second crux with the thumbs up hand jam into the thumbs up finger jam. Holding onto it almost like a pinch helps. Awkward section follows into big jugs out left. First clean TR.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: A nice climb, a little more thoughtful and clear beta’d than Anasazi.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: A much better approach to setting up a TR on Makunaima. Pretty straight up until the final pull to the chains, look out for a good hold over the lip to the right, anything else is desperate.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > Gibraltar Area > Cold Springs Dome > Makunaima Amphitheater

Notes: Can do all but dunk the cross over move and I’m close. Big move with left hand. Left foot up, right foot put right and perch and drag the foot hard. Right hand to crimp side pull. To make the cross over stand hard on your right foot. Dynamically match, high right and throw hard for the final hold!
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > * Santa Barbara Bouldering > Skofield Park > Cracked Boulder

Notes: Led odds, did .10- finger crack finish. Soooo good. Pitches 1 and 3 are excellent and very steep. Pitches 2 and 4 are mediocre. Pitch 5 has mouth watering locks. Not as consistent in quality as crimson gem, but the odd pitches are just too good.
Location: California > High Sierra > 02 - The Sawtooth Ridge > The Juggernaut

Notes: Led all but last pitch with Roy who was down bad with low stoke but at least the climb cheered him up. First pitch is punchy. Second pitch double cracks are sweet. Third pitch corner is steep with interesting pods. Fourth pitch Aframe is super cool. Fifth pitch we did the 5.8 finish to dihedral route and it went on forever! Splitter fun, overall pretty easy for the grade. Approach, summit and descent all incredibly beautiful.
Location: California > High Sierra > 02 - The Sawtooth Ridge > The Juggernaut

Notes: Excellent climb. Getting established in the corner not so bad with movement on the arete and out right. Super cool movement inside the corner and on the arete then on. Eases up considerably in the final third.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Horseshoe Piles > Spring Wall

Notes: Very good route. Gaining the ledge takes some good beta. Then the crux is firing for that jug. Steep but juggy climbing then on. Easy ground after turning the lip.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Horseshoe Piles > Spring Wall

Notes: Just a less good version of the 5.9 to the left.

Notes: Way more fun than I thought it would be. Engaging crux to the chains.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Horseshoe Piles > Spring Wall

Notes: Warmup. The pull around always gets the face climbing head on straight.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Dike Wall > North Face

Notes: Throwing up the rope for my boys, always enjoy this climb, demands good beta.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Dike Wall > East Face

Notes: One hang, but cruised the rest of it and blew through the crux after a rest hang. Some cool layback-y type stuff through the grooves leads to the step across. Just go big out right, try to find feet to reduce rotation and release and catch. After that is the crux. My beta is as follows: LH on jug near hips, reach way high with RH to dark right facing hold. Bring LH just under and to the right of RH near wrist to good crimp (positive on right side). Don’t bother with the crimp to the right of that. RF on a little nub (hard to see) so you can get laybacky body language. Trust your RF, and get LF on obvious chalky foot chip near center (crux). Bump RF to something to keep balance and LH out to pinch, RF up to rail and RH up to jug and done! Alt beta seems to be to go hands on the crimps, left foot high to chalky foot chip and crank to the seam, simpler but you have to pull hard on that lil crimp I didn’t use.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Lake George > Dike Wall > East Face

Notes: Very rad climb, long with lots of fun sections. Hand rail is hero, upper finger crack is locker, awkward section midway up on the left trending ramp.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Rock Creek > Gong Show Wall

Notes: Even better than sideshow. Meaty layback to start, interesting face section then rad corner movement. Five star route for sure.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Rock Creek > Gong Show Wall

Notes: TR lap after. Clean send. Don’t forget the little rail inside the wide crack when you cross over it. To pull the crux I felt good getting my left foot onto an alright chip knee-ish height and punching for it.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Rock Creek > Gong Show Wall

Notes: Two hangs at the crux. Face moves through bolts are not negligible. After stepping out right, stepping back left is a little weird. Look for a foot chip for your left foot and a crimp for your right hand and pull in. Easy hand crack. Finger crack has a good foot for the first half, plug a 0.2 in the small pod before the final lock, you don’t need to use it anyway. Reach far right to get a sinker lock, make sure it’s good. You’ll have no good feet here on out. Get your right hand over and into the finger crack at the bottom of the pod, find an okay foot, and fire hard way up and in for a good thumbs down hand jam. Rest is cruiser.
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Mammoth Lakes Area > Rock Creek > Gong Show Wall

Notes: Dogged and pulled through the first two bolts. Shit is nails hard. Would be wild without a stick clip. Rest of route is fun.
Location: California > Central Coast > Hwy 33/Ojai > Wheeler Gorge

Notes: Did this years ago. Warmup today. A nice climb but I don’t love climbing cobbles.

Notes: This route was a bit of a disappointment. It’s just so hard to not to use the arette. It either feels too easy or too hard. Cool position. The lack of a bolt down low is laughable.

Route: Regular Northwest Face of Half Dome (RNWF)
Notes: What an awesome time on a great route. With Roy. Led pitches 1,4,7,10-15,18-23. Free climbed pretty much all the followed pitches. Hiked death slabs the day before, Roy almost went down a slab on a slick rock crossing. Fixed first two pitches that day and slept staring at the wall. Didn’t sleep a wink because of the mosquitos. Woke at 4 to get rocking. Hit pitch after pitch of stellar climbing and aid. First third, the pillar, went smooth enough. Second third, the traverse then up to big sandy we lost some time waiting for the German dudes ahead of us to rope toss. Got mine on the ~10th try. Triple linkup of the chimney pitches was a highlight. Zig zags also went in a triple linkup. All time moment walking the thank god ledge with my back to the wall. Legs shaking one shuffle at a time! Topped out just after dark, something like 16ish hours on route if I’m being nice. Hiked literally all night to get back to the valley floor via Mist trail. Super beat, but one of my fav climbing experiences of all time!

Notes: With Eric Newcomb. Astroboys. Retreated after Harding slot. Recommend to pitch out the wandering start and the .10a section, rope drag was gnarly. Boulder problem is tough but good gear. Piker’s variation is stiff stemming but not crazy hard. Would recommend 2x 0.1’s if you want to do that. Enduro corner is crazy long and steep. Thin hands on the steep part, milk the hand jams and looks for stems. Hard line finger jamming up high. Easy 5.9 pitch is nice and chill. The next pitch is .10c and relatively relaxed, lots of good hand jams. Remember the small nuts for a key placement near the layback up high. The Harding slot pretty crazy. Steep layback is punchy but doable if you power it up. Entry moves are cryptic but requires creative use of heel + knee/hip. Gear is good and there is a nice rest before you dive in. It is a pretty relaxed squeeze until a body length from when it widens. It really squeezes there. I couldn’t get myself to get forward progress. Eric recommended “pencilling” where your legs are straight up and down instead of typical splayed froggy legs. Cam your feet HEEL UP bringing the top knuckles of your toe in contact instead of typical heel down and extend your legs using double arm bars at chest-ish height. This method gets you a half inch at a time so it’ll take something like 100+ reps of this movement. Breathe out as you extend up. Don’t get suckered into the outside once you’re in, it’s too tight. It wasn’t as scary as I thought because you can always just slide back down, I don’t think you can get “stuck”. Maybe with the pencil method I can make it through next time. Overall I’m pretty stoked about my effort. I was definitely trying to punch above my weight but I’m glad I gave it a go.

Lots of falls on crux. .10~ thin hands to hands down low. Once you’re forced to step off the tower, there are good locks to lay off. Be strong and move until you can reach for the big hold, two 0.3’s on the left hip critical. Rightmost side of upper hold is positive for left hand. Right foot cornered as high as possible, pull hard to slam a pinky/ring int  on the obvious lock. Pull hard to high step left foot. Gear is good and climbing easy once you’ve set that foot. Super tight climb should give a go if you’re here next time!

Legend has it alternative beta is to find a part of the lower hold that allows you to set bodyweight right, allowing you to use the right facing edge better for your foot and right hand thumbs down up to lock. Like the picture.

Notes: 3 nights, 3.5 days. W/ Ross Goldberg. First day was freeblast, rapped to ground and hauled back up to heart. Second day to the spire. Led the hollow flake, panted like a dog after topping it, no pro makes for an epic pitch. Also led the ear, invert Bombay chimney is fucked up. Had to remove my glasses to turn my head. Partner bonked on the ear follow, had to pick up all the rest of the leads to the spire. Spanning the spire gap in the dark was epic. Third day to long ledge. Led all the wide pitches and C2 crux pitches. Sous le toit, enduro corner and roof pitch all super cool. Made it to headwall, position is insane. Partner took three whips off of C2 crux of headwall. I had to step up for it. I blew a fluke placement leaving the belay in the C1, factor 2’d, flipped upside down, rope wrapped around Ross’s neck, instantly knocked him out, I realized from his limp body and gurgling what was going on. I managed to grab onto the portaledge hanging below the haul bag and unweighted the rope, Ross immediately regained consciousness and removed rope from neck, was in confused panic. I was still hanging in free space, unsure if Ross could hold me in a factor 2 position in his state. I frantically managed to grab a ladder and attach it the bottom of the bag, ascended through Ross’s ladders back to belay. Ross super shaken understandably, said he felt like he was dreaming for hours, neck bruised and burnt but no serious damage somehow. I managed to calm him down and lead the C2 crux fine. Got to long ledge, thin sleeping. Ross actually in good spirits despite his strangulation. Chose to lead 5.10 C1 off long ledge, crazy exposed and interesting climbing. Blasted to the top. felt like I had to step up and perform constantly to get to the top of this thing, certainly one of the hardest things I’ve ever done. Emotionally shaken up from the strangulation, shit happens but I don’t want anyone to get irreparably hurt. I’m not broken but I’m badly bent.
Location: California > Yosemite National Park > Yosemite Valley > Valley North Side > B. El Capitan > 2. Southwest Face

Notes: Ticking as we did freeblast.
Location: California > Yosemite National Park > Yosemite Valley > Valley North Side > B. El Capitan > 1. Base Routes > Southwest Base > Moby Dick and Pterodactyl Terrace

Notes: Proudly sent P1/P2 linked. P3 roof is hard pulled on gear, but I think doable. Need to figure out how to move hands across the underclings. P4 is very fun tips LB and stemming, good gear, clean on follow. P5 is scary! Kept it together until it was time to pull the bulge, stepped well above my piece, couldn’t reach the bolt, then took a big whipper with a pulled cam! First big free climbing fall on the big stone! Aided past the section and then French freed the rest of the pitch. P6 is more hard slab, frenched hard. P6 is low key. P8 the half dollar is heinous. Not so bad through the roof but getting into it… wtf, slickest rock ever. The actual wide is fine because there’s a good crack in the back. From there it’s easy 5.7. Stoked to get on this! Maybe one day I can free the hard stuff.
Location: California > Yosemite National Park > Yosemite Valley > Valley North Side > B. El Capitan > 2. Southwest Face
California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Echo Cliffs > Java Wall
California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Echo Cliffs > Java Wall

Notes:
2 tries. Pretty solid efforts.

B5 beta: don’t clip until you’re at the undercling. Pull hard to it the holds aren’t greats

B6 beta: key hold has a L facing edge. Right hand is on the up facing edge. Transfer Lhand to hold, right hand goes to R facing hold stomach height, set up for throw, throw not bad.

B9 beta: there’s a palm out rest out left to clip B8. Use that hold on the left wall above it. Then you can stem to pull into the side pulls. There’s that hueco thing for your right and a flake to the left that is deep if you can get into it. Fire to the chains.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Echo Cliffs > Java Wall

Notes: Failed onsight at last bolt. Definitely the crux. Steep but pretty smooth sailing up till then and an excellent rest at the overlap. Very nice climb. Red pointed right after.
Location: California > Los Angeles Basin > Santa Monica Mountains > Echo Cliffs > Java Wall

Notes: Sandy and sequential, make sure you’re moving the correct foot up lest you flounder. A sweet route for sure.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > San Ysidro

Notes: Barefoot for funsies.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > San Ysidro

Notes: Set up for Justin B and Nate and to access TR for vanishing flakes. Would make a nice first trad lead.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > San Ysidro

Notes: Very nice climbing. Went direct to first bolt on the lower, a contrived reach move imo. Lots of opportunity for good lockoffs and foot positioning here.
Location: California > Central Coast > Santa Barbara > San Ysidro

Notes:
With Luke In 6 technical pitches. Led P1/P2 link, P4/P5 link, and P7. Simuled some from lower to middle tower, solod the rest. 3:30 wake up, 4:10 leave camp, 5:10 arrive at base, 5:40 begin climbing by headlamp, 12:40 top of final technical pitch, 4:30 at the very tippy top, 7:40 back at camp.

This is a fricken mountain man, so huge.

The first pitch had me shaking at the crux, and pumped thereafter. Super sick corner climbing. The rest is steep and fun 5.8 with two very nice .10a cruxes. The ridge kinda sucks, bad rock and hard to read. I really enjoyed the shelves up to the peak.

Getting down took awhile, but the climb is massive so what do you expect.

Luke and I feel like we really crushed this climb and are super stoked!
Location: California > High Sierra > 09 - Palisades & Surrounding Peaks > Temple Crag

Notes: Soooo good. Juggy and steep. Lots of crack sizes so you need to be comfortable with it all. Went right at the top. The inside of the crack is so flat and the edge so sharp, spliiiiiiiterville!
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Bishop Area > Cardinal Pinnacle

Notes: Led P2,4. Very fun route, even better than west face. P2 crux is fingers deep in a flare, fun. P3 is the money, so many excellent finger sections. P4 is a quick layback crux, lean hard!
Location: California > Sierra Eastside > Bishop Area > Cardinal Pinnacle

Notes: Led P1,3. Fell twice on the P2 follow. Absolutely crushed P3 and super proud for it! Absolutely coming back to redpoint P2 and go for gram. For P1, 0.2 in leftmost crack and traverse over, 1 hard move. Move to get to first P2 bolt is actually not bad. For P2 crux, left foot on rail and reach mega far. Two more mantles cruxes and you're good. Trip 0.4, 0.5, 0.75 is plenty for P3.

Notes: Led 5.5 pitch and crux pitch. This thing is amazing, best views, crazy unique climbing, we blew through it too.

Notes: Middle P1 var. led P1,4,5. Fell on the .10c down step as a follower. Slammed into the slab, feet first at least. .10a crux is seriously smeary, pulled on a cam to get through it and really enjoyed the lay backing to the top.
Location: California > Yosemite National Park > Tuolumne Meadows > Daff Area > Daff Dome > West Face

Notes: One small fall (on a 000!) in the layback feet to knob transition. Otherwise, I totally styled this route. Good gear, and never too pumpy, just be smart with ya feet! Would love to do this climb again.

Double 0.3-1, single 2,3,4. 70m for rap is chill until the P1 rap, and then 20ft of 5.4 downclimbing, would do again. If you want to link P4, make sure you save two draws, two 0.5’s and a 0.3.
